ol in Mexican and Chicano culture, examining the image of the soldadera in literature, corridos, art, music, and film. Challenging many traditional stereotypes, Salas finds that the fundamental realities of war link all Mexican women, regardless of time period, social class, or nom de guerre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexico-Armed Forces-Women-History. 0aWomen and the militaryzMexicoxHistory. 0aWomen and the military-Mexico-History. 0aWomenxArmed ForceszMexicoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77630240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292757080423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292757080/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK